Final Project: Recommendation Systems

Shyni David

6/6/2019

Using the movielens data as in (1), limit yourself to movies from the years 2000 to 2016.

1. Explore the data, and propose a system to bucketize the ratings on the Low-high scale (0-1). For instance, you may consider a way to deal with individual-level anchoring levels as you have see in other classes. Provide descriptive evidence of the variability in ratings.

2. Create a testing and a training subset. Id suggest leaving 10% out

3. Build (and tune, see (1)) a recommendation system using both User-Based and Item-Based CF algorithms with different similarity measures (cosine vs.Pearson etc) and providing recommendation for the top 7 movies.

4. Evaluate the performance of both algorithms in the testing set.

A collaborative filtering recommender (CFR) system is being used where filtering approach is based only on user preferences rather than movie features or contents. If two users share the same interests in the past then the recommender predicts similar taste in future.

Creating the Rating matrix

ratingmat <- dcast(movie_ratings_02, userId~movieId, value.var = "rating", na.rm=FALSE)
ratingmat <- as.matrix(ratingmat[,-1])  

#Convert rating matrix into a recommenderlab sparse matrix
ratingmat <- as(ratingmat, "realRatingMatrix")
ratingmat
## 431 x 4453 rating matrix of class 'realRatingMatrix' with 31882 ratings.

In order to use the rating data for building recommendation engine with recommenderlab, we converted rating matrix into a sparse matrix of type realRatingMatrix. The rows asre userid and the columns are movieID and the values are the ratings.

Binarizing data Also the rating can be more of aspirational values rather than revealed values. The Likert Scale is the most universal method of survey collection. it does not force the participant to take a stand on a topic but allows them to respond in degree of agreement. The dis-advantage is that it is uni-dimensional and gives ony 5-7 options of choice and the space between the choices cannot possibly be equidistant. And it is not unlikely that users answers will be influenced and may not be his/her real response.

Some recommendation model work on binary data, so it might be useful to binarize the data, that is define a table containing only 0s and 1s. There may be manyscenarios:

  • Define a matrix having 1 if the user rated the movies and 0 otherwise. In this case, the information about the rating scale is lost.
ratings_movies_watched <- binarize(ratings_movies, minRating = 1)
min_movies_binary <- quantile(rowCounts(ratings_movies), 0.95)
min_users_binary <- quantile(colCounts(ratings_movies), 0.95)
image(ratings_movies_watched[rowCounts(ratings_movies) > min_movies_binary,
                             colCounts(ratings_movies) > min_users_binary], 
main = "Heatmap of the top users and movies")

  • Define a matrix having 1 if the rating is above or equal to a threshold (for example 2) and 0 otherwise. In this case, giving a bad rating to movie is equivalent to not having rated it.
ratings_movies_good <- binarize(ratings_movies, minRating = 2)
image(ratings_movies_good[rowCounts(ratings_movies) > min_movies_binary, 
colCounts(ratings_movies) > min_users_binary], 
main = "Heatmap of the top users and movies")

  • Define a matrix having 1 if the rating is above or equal to a threshold (for example 3) and 0 otherwise. In this case, giving a bad rating to movie is equivalent to not having rated it.
ratings_movies_good <- binarize(ratings_movies, minRating = 3)
image(ratings_movies_good[rowCounts(ratings_movies) > min_movies_binary, 
colCounts(ratings_movies) > min_users_binary], 
main = "Heatmap of the top users and movies")

There are more white cells in the third heat map, which shows there are more movies with no or bad ratings.

ITEM based Collaborative Filtering Model The word Collaborative means users collaborate with each other to recommend items. We use the rating matrix in which rows correspond to UserID and columns correspond to movieId. The core algorithm is based on these steps: 1. For each two movies, measure how similar they are in terms of ratings received. 2. For each movie, identify the k most similar movies. 3. For each user, identify the movies that are the most similar to the users ratings.

Defining training/test sets

set.seed(1234)
train_data  <- sample(x = c(TRUE, FALSE), 
                      size = nrow(ratings_movies),
                      replace = TRUE, 
                      prob = c(0.8, 0.2))
recc_train <- ratings_movies[train_data, ]
recc_test <- ratings_movies[-train_data, ]

Building the Recommendation Model default parameters of IBCF model. Here,
k is the number of items to compute the similarities among them in the first step. After, for each item, the algorithm identifies its k most similar items and stores the number.
method is a similarity funtion, which is Cosine by default, may also be pearson. We create the model using the default parameters of method = Cosine and k=30.

recommender_models <- recommenderRegistry$get_entries(dataType ="realRatingMatrix")

Its dimensions are 281 X 281 which is equal to the number of movies.

The heat map of the first 20 rows and columns show that many values are 0. Each row contains k =30 elements that are greater than 0. The matrix is not symmetric. The number of non-null elements for each column depends on how many times the corresponding movie was included in the top k of another movie.

The chart of the distribution of the number of elements by columns shows that there are few movies that are similar to many others.

Applying Recommender system on the dataset
Now, it is possible to recommend movies to the users in the test set.

Define n_recommended equal to 10 that specifies the number of movies to recommend to each user.

For each user, the algorithm extracts its rated movies. For each movie, it identifies all its similar movies, starting from the similarity matrix. Then, the algorithm ranks each similar movies in this way:

  • Extract the user rating associated with this movie. The rating is used as a weight.
  • Extract the similarity of the movie with each rating associated with this movie.
  • Multiply each weight with the related similarity.
  • Sum everything up.

Then, the algorithm identifies the top 10 recommendations:

recc_predicted <- predict(object = recc_model, 
                          newdata = recc_test, 
                          n = 10)
recc_predicted
## Recommendations as 'topNList' with n = 10 for 233 users.

IBCF recommends items on the basis of the similarity matrix. For each item, the model stores the k-most similar, so the amount of information is small once the model is built. This is an advantage in the presence of lots of data.

In addition, this algorithm is efficient and scalable, so it works well with big rating matrices.

USER-based Collaborative Filtering Model

According to this approach, given a new user, its similar users are first identified. Then, the top-rated movies rated by similar users are recommended.

For each new user, these are the steps:

  1. Measure how similar each user is to the new one. Like IBCF, popular similarity measures are correlation and cosine.
  2. Identify the most similar users. The options are:
  • Take account of the top k users (k-nearest_neighbors)
  • Take account of the users whose similarity is above a defined threshold
  1. Rate the movies rated by the most similar users. The rating is the average rating among similar users and the approaches are:
  • Average rating
  • Weighted average rating, using the similarities as weights
  1. Pick the top-rated movies.
Building the recommendation system:

Again, lets first check the default parameters of UBCF model. Here, nn is a number of similar users, and method is a similarity function, which is cosine by default.

Evaluating the Recommender Systems

There are a few options to choose from when deciding to create a recommendation engine. In order to compare their performances and choose the most appropriate model:

  • Prepare the data to evaluate performance
  • Evaluate the performance of some models
  • Choose the best performing models
  • Optimize model parameters
Preparing the data to evaluate models

Splitting the data into training and test sets is often done using a 80/20 proportion and then using k-fold.

For each user in the test set, we need to define how many novies to use to generate recommendations. For this, first check the minimum number of movies rated by users to be sure there will be no users with no items to test.

min(rowCounts(ratings_movies)) 
## [1] 7
#number of movies to generate recommendations
movies_to_keep <- 5 
# threshold with the minimum rating that is considered good
rating_threshold <- 3 
#number of times to run evaluation
n_eval <- 1 

eval_sets <- evaluationScheme(data = ratings_movies, 
                              method = "split",
                              train = 0.80, 
                              given = movies_to_keep, 
                              goodRating = rating_threshold, 
                              k = n_eval)

The above image displays the unknown items by the users, which varies a lot.

Using cross-validation to validate models

The k-fold cross-validation approach is the most accurate one, although its computationally heavier.

Using this approach, we split the data into some chunks, take a chunk out as the test set, and evaluate the accuracy. Then, we can do the same with each other chunk and compute the average accuracy.

#using K= 4-fold 
eval_sets <- evaluationScheme(data = ratings_movies, 
                              method = "cross-validation",
                              k = 4, 
                              given = movies_to_keep, 
                              goodRating = rating_threshold)
size_sets <- sapply(eval_sets@runsTrain, length)
size_sets
## [1] 174 174 174 174

Using 4-fold approach, we get four sets of the same size 174.

Evavluating the ratings

First, re-define the evaluation sets, build IBCF model and create a matrix with predicted ratings.

Evaluating the recommendations

Another way to measure accuracies is by comparing the recommendations with the purchases having a positive rating. For this, make use of a prebuilt evaluate function in recommenderlab library. The function evaluate the recommender performance depending on the number n of items to recommend to each user. Use n as a sequence n = seq(10, 100, 10). The first rows of the resulting performance matrix is presented below:

results <- evaluate(x = eval_sets, 
                    method = "IBCF", 
                    n = seq(5, 20, 2))

Plot the ROC and the precision/recall curves:

#IBCF
plot(results, annotate = TRUE, main = "ROC curve-IBCF")

plot(results, "prec/rec", annotate = TRUE, main = "Precision-recall-IBCF")

#UBCF
plot(results1, annotate = TRUE, main = "ROC curve-UBCF")

plot(results1, "prec/rec", annotate = TRUE, main = "Precision-recall-UBCF")

The ROC curve, higher the areas for a certain combination of parameters the better, IBCF and UBCF both seems to have the ROC, so not a clear winner.

For the precision-recall, UBCF seems to be universally better, higher precision and higher recall. For IBCF, it may do better with UBCF, if we could leverage item information for a portfolio of upto 7 movies.

If a small percentage of rated movies is recommended, the precision decreases. On the other hand, the higher percentage of rated movies is recommended the higher is the recall.

Comparing models

In order to compare different models, define them as a following list:

  • Item-based collaborative filtering, using the Cosine as the distance function
  • Item-based collaborative filtering, using the Pearson correlation as the distance function
  • User-based collaborative filtering, using the Cosine as the distance function
  • User-based collaborative filtering, using the Pearson correlation as the distance function
  • Random recommendations to have a base line
models_to_evaluate <- list(
IBCF_cos = list(name = "IBCF", 
                param = list(method = "cosine")),
IBCF_cor = list(name = "IBCF", 
                param = list(method = "pearson")),
UBCF_cos = list(name = "UBCF", 
                param = list(method = "cosine")),
UBCF_cor = list(name = "UBCF", 
                param = list(method = "pearson")),
random = list(name = "RANDOM", param=NULL)
)

Define a different set of numbers for recommended movies (n_recommendations <- c(1, 5, seq(10, 100, 10))), run and evaluate the models:

n_recommendations <- c(1, 5, seq(10, 100, 10))
list_results <- evaluate(x = eval_sets, 
                         method = models_to_evaluate, 
                         n = n_recommendations)

Identifying the most suitable model

Compare the models by building a chart displaying their ROC curves and Precision/recall curves.

plot(list_results, annotate = 1, legend = "topleft") 
title("ROC curve")

plot(list_results, "prec/rec", annotate = 1, legend = "topright")
title("Precision-recall")

A good performance index is the area under the curve (AUC), that is, the area under the ROC curve. Even without computing it, the chart shows that the highest is UBCF with Pearson distance, so its the best-performing technique.

The advantage of User based Collaborative Filtering is that it gives recommendations that can be complements to the movies the user has rated. This might be a stronger recommendation than with movie based recommender as users might not be looking for direct substitutes to a movie.

The disadvantage of User based Collaborative filtering is that its a type of memory based collaborative filtering that uses all user data in the database to create recommendations. It has the issue of huge computational cost ad limited scalability. Also UBCF relies on the past user choices to make future recommendations and this might be true always.
